n, from their teenage years through older adulthood, asserted agency through social practices, speech acts, legal disputes, writing, viewing and exchanging images, travel, and community building. Despite family and social pressures, the actions of girls and women could shape their lives and challenge male-dominated institutions. This volume includes thirteen essays by scholars from many disciplines, which analyze people, texts, objects, and images from many different parts of Europe, as well as things and people that crossed the Atlantic and the Pacific.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aFeminismzEuropexHistory. 0aWomenzEuropexHistory. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aHISTORY / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aWomen's agency, early modern, women's writing, material culture, gender.1 aBeranek, Saskia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoswell, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, Julie D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastiglione, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDinan, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacobsen, Grethe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKemp, Theresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLink, Beth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcShane, Angela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNelson, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOsherow, Michele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOwens, Sarah 